After the return of Caesar, Cicero took little part in politics. He did not sympathize with the uncompromising attitude of the senate, he was hurt by the coldness of Pompey towards himself, and disappointed by that leader's selfish aims. While appreciating the irresistible power ot the Triumvirate, he saw a ray ot hope in the apparent unpopularity ol the triumvirs,⁴ whose rule, he believed, could not last long. Clodius continued straight on toward his cherished purpose ol avenging himself upon Cicero With that end in view he caused himself to be adopted by a plebeian, Fonteius, and secured an election as tribune 'l for the year 58.
